<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Multidistrict Lit Man § 10:5<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Multidistrict Litigation Manual</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20190501"><bop/><bos/>May 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>David F. Herr[<footnote.reference refid="If66a0b416b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">a0</footnote.reference>]</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I97b7f560933b11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Part</label.name><label.designator>I.</label.designator><headtext>Handling Cases Before the Judicial Panel on Multidistrict Litigation</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I6059a720933c11da99e2b07024dacc26"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>10.</label.designator><headtext>Remand</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copyright (c) 2017 Thomson/RIA All rights reserved.</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="I94fa0518e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>10:5.</label.designator><headtext>Effect of remand</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The effect of an order remanding a case to the transferor court for trial is to divest the transferee court of jurisdiction in the case and to vest the transferor court with jurisdiction. <eos/><bos/>The transferor court receives the case as the third court handling the case. <eos/><bos/>The Panel&apos;s initial transfer order and the remand order are both orders of transfer.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The transferor court (court to which the actions are remanded) receives the cases in the condition they are in at the time of remand. <eos/><bos/>Decisions that have been made in the case continue to apply unless circumstances change warranting their modification.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If66a32506b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">1</footnote.reference>] The decisions made by the transferee court are considered “law of the case.”[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If66a32516b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If66a0b416b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If66a32506b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><ital>See, e.g.</ital>, <cite.query w-src-number="0304914135" w-serial-number="1996280010" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000344" w-pinpoint-page="636" ID="I700a53216b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">In re Factor VIII or IX Concentrate Blood Products Litigation, 169 F.R.D. 632, 636 (N.D. Ill. 1996)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0304914135" w-serial-number="1981109304" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" ID="I700a53236b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">In re Upjohn Co. Antibiotic Cleocin Products Liability Litigation, 508 F. Supp. 1020 (E.D. Mich. 1981)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If66a32516b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0304914135" w-serial-number="1971112570" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000350" ID="I700aef616b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">Allegheny Airlines, Inc. v. LeMay, 448 F.2d 1341 (7th Cir. 1971)</cite.query>, <case.history>cert. denied</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0304914135" w-serial-number="1971201894" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I700aef646b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">404 U.S. 1001, 92 S. Ct. 565, 30 L. Ed. 2d 553 (1971)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0304914135" w-serial-number="1982126123" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000345" ID="I700aef676b3e11e9924ce6bc9a15439b">Sentner v. Amtrak, 540 F. Supp. 557 (D.N.J. 1982)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>MDLITMAN § 10:5<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
